1
00:00:12,247 --> 00:00:20,740
This is my new Logitech Fandango and you are now seeing me in my full glory.

2
00:00:20,760 --> 00:00:24,426
I only hope you had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:24,446 --> 00:00:28,012
I do not say happy, but I hope it has been happy.

4
00:00:29,033 --> 00:00:36,265
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambhodassa

5
00:00:36,987 --> 00:00:45,856
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambodasa.

6
00:00:45,877 --> 00:00:53,987
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambodasa.

7
00:00:54,728 --> 00:01:00,554
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

8
00:01:00,575 --> 00:01:03,518
So just as I was getting you my own face,

9
00:01:04,325 --> 00:01:11,111
just as I was getting used to looking at my own face while I'm talking, I'm now looking at an object in the middle of the room.

10
00:01:11,671 --> 00:01:13,433
A bit like being on radio, I suppose.

11
00:01:14,034 --> 00:01:15,396
So I've got to get used to that now.

12
00:01:15,436 --> 00:01:18,799
Anyway, we're still on the taints.

13
00:01:19,579 --> 00:01:20,021
Oh, yes.

14
00:01:20,281 --> 00:01:21,162
Can't leave the taints.

15
00:01:23,243 --> 00:01:28,228
Just to remind you that we have seven taints here.

16
00:01:28,248 --> 00:01:31,091
Let me just read them through.

17
00:01:31,111 --> 00:01:32,192
It's good to revise them.

18
00:01:32,774 --> 00:01:34,094
There is the...

19
00:01:35,121 --> 00:01:38,906
The taint by seeing, which is through insight, remember.

20
00:01:39,507 --> 00:01:40,507
Let me just get this straight.

21
00:01:40,548 --> 00:01:41,769
That's better.

22
00:01:41,789 --> 00:01:53,522
The insight through overcoming the taint, especially on not-self, the false sense of I through vipassana.

23
00:01:54,162 --> 00:01:58,847
And then we had one by restraint, by restraining ourselves.

24
00:01:58,908 --> 00:02:02,951
Then we abandoned them by using things better.

25
00:02:03,370 --> 00:02:07,174
And now we have to abandon things by enduring.

26
00:02:07,213 --> 00:02:14,540
So the quality here, of course, is patience.

27
00:02:14,561 --> 00:02:15,983
The Buddha is big on patience.

28
00:02:16,562 --> 00:02:23,129
The highest form of ascetic practice by which he means ascetic practice is renunciation.

29
00:02:23,169 --> 00:02:30,137
It's the highest form of renunciation because you are renouncing reaction to what is unpleasant.

30
00:02:31,467 --> 00:02:33,449
So let's read what he says here.

31
00:02:34,292 --> 00:02:37,676
What taints Bhikkhus should be abandoned by enduring?

32
00:02:38,598 --> 00:02:52,361
Here, reflecting wisely, he bears cold and heat, hunger and thirst, contact with gadflies, mosquitoes, wind, the sun, creeping things and COVID-19.

33
00:02:53,826 --> 00:03:06,258
He endures ill-spoken, unwelcome words and arisen bodily feelings that are painful, wracking, sharp, piercing, disagreeable, distressing and menacing to life.

34
00:03:07,658 --> 00:03:23,513
While taints, vexation and fever, so vexation is the aversion, fever is the desire, might arise in one who does not endure such things, there are no taints, vexation or fever in one who endures them.

35
00:03:24,877 --> 00:03:29,100
And these are called overcoming the taints by enduring.

36
00:03:29,561 --> 00:03:41,872
So if we just look at one or two areas where we find ourselves getting very irritated and all that sort of stuff, there are those little niggly irritations, aren't there?

37
00:03:42,854 --> 00:03:47,698
Leaving the freezer door open and finding that it's all iced up on the door.

38
00:03:48,057 --> 00:03:49,500
And then you sort of kick it too.

39
00:03:51,241 --> 00:03:54,123
The toaster...

40
00:03:54,694 --> 00:04:03,581
When you set it wrongly and it's burnt the toast, all these little irritations, sort of an impatience with things too.

41
00:04:04,383 --> 00:04:06,585
It's surprising how everything has to be now.

42
00:04:06,944 --> 00:04:07,725
Everything has to be now.

43
00:04:08,947 --> 00:04:16,153
I read somewhere that Amazon spent millions on getting this immediate delivery, you know, what do they call it?

44
00:04:16,233 --> 00:04:18,274
Prime Amazon or something.

45
00:04:18,795 --> 00:04:24,600
So that as soon as you've clicked on your box of chocolate, you can hear it drop in your letterbox.

46
00:04:24,951 --> 00:04:28,014
That's how we're demanding that everything has to be now.

47
00:04:29,416 --> 00:04:33,721
In fact, I have to express a certain impatience myself here, confess to it.

48
00:04:33,742 --> 00:04:42,432
This little gadget I'm looking at, I did actually order through Amazon and after about two weeks gave up on them and went on to eBay.

49
00:04:42,752 --> 00:04:45,855
Now, that doesn't mean to say that I prefer eBay to Amazon.

50
00:04:45,875 --> 00:04:48,158
It's just that I finally got it on eBay.

51
00:04:50,247 --> 00:04:57,521
But I just remember my concern bordering on a certain annoyance that it hadn't been delivered.

52
00:04:59,463 --> 00:05:00,605
Then there are neighbours.

53
00:05:00,747 --> 00:05:02,069
Neighbours, oh, my goodness.

54
00:05:02,730 --> 00:05:05,435
You know, if you have a noisy neighbour, it can drive you potty.

55
00:05:05,495 --> 00:05:05,956
I know it.

56
00:05:06,677 --> 00:05:09,622
I used to live in, you know, these two up, two downs.

57
00:05:09,939 --> 00:05:15,069
And my next door neighbor had a real love of Elvis Presley.

58
00:05:15,569 --> 00:05:21,959
Now, I myself like Elvis Presley, but not all the time and not the volume that she would play it.

59
00:05:22,761 --> 00:05:26,447
And I had to go down once and asked her to turn it low.

60
00:05:26,507 --> 00:05:28,029
I said, do you mind just turning it low?

61
00:05:28,451 --> 00:05:30,653
And her reply was, I pay my rates.

62
00:05:31,615 --> 00:05:32,557
I thought, well, OK.

63
00:05:33,639 --> 00:05:34,300
Anyway, she did.

64
00:05:34,341 --> 00:05:35,221
She was very kind.

65
00:05:36,281 --> 00:05:45,170
But yes, neighbours, those little noises from the TV or from music coming to the walls.

66
00:05:48,374 --> 00:05:54,360
And this reminds me of when I used to go to Sri Lanka or the East, but mainly in Sri Lanka.

67
00:05:56,201 --> 00:06:01,766
When I first got there and I had this beautiful little hut, this kuti hut,

68
00:06:02,319 --> 00:06:04,704
And the squirrels were around.

69
00:06:05,004 --> 00:06:10,994
And what they used to do was they used to climb along the beams of my walking.

70
00:06:12,497 --> 00:06:14,600
There was a channel for walking, a chankama.

71
00:06:15,963 --> 00:06:19,148
And they were at the wood to get the grubs out.

72
00:06:19,533 --> 00:06:23,418
And this, of course, I found tremendously disturbing.

73
00:06:23,858 --> 00:06:36,492
And then there was this, what you might call, cartoon moment when I jumped off the cushion that I was sitting on and ran down the corridor waving this flag and beating these beans.

74
00:06:36,994 --> 00:06:40,939
I mean, these days, if that had been caught on camera, it would definitely have gone viral.

75
00:06:42,379 --> 00:06:43,682
And, of course, I went back.

76
00:06:43,862 --> 00:06:44,762
They disappeared.

77
00:06:45,223 --> 00:06:46,185
And I thought, that's that.

78
00:06:46,204 --> 00:06:49,488
And, of course, as soon as I sat down again, they were at it, scratching away.

79
00:06:50,060 --> 00:06:52,884
So, of course, one has to accept these things, you see.

80
00:06:52,904 --> 00:06:55,228
Noises in the east.

81
00:06:55,470 --> 00:07:01,802
I only remember real quietness descending around about one o'clock at night.

82
00:07:02,382 --> 00:07:06,649
I used to wake up in a real quietness, two o'clock, and then it would all start at about three o'clock.

83
00:07:07,512 --> 00:07:12,961
But even in the absolute quietness, there would be no crickets or anything like that, cicadas.

84
00:07:14,495 --> 00:07:16,036
So there was always noise.

85
00:07:16,057 --> 00:07:18,862
And I remember I came back once.

86
00:07:19,762 --> 00:07:21,144
I had to return to England.

87
00:07:21,305 --> 00:07:23,408
My mother and father died during that time.

88
00:07:23,990 --> 00:07:27,896
And I came back and noise was just overwhelming.

89
00:07:27,935 --> 00:07:36,649
The birds, the squirrels, there were these set of birds that squeaked to each other all the time.

90
00:07:36,689 --> 00:07:40,536
They're called the seven sisters and they don't stop talking.

91
00:07:40,786 --> 00:07:49,779
And then I noticed that, of course, as soon as I stopped getting irritated, within a day or two, I didn't hear them.

92
00:07:50,199 --> 00:07:51,100
This is the point, isn't it?

93
00:07:52,182 --> 00:07:56,228
You know, as soon as you're angry, as soon as you're irritated, your ear sticks on it.

94
00:07:56,949 --> 00:08:08,767
And as soon as you stop being averse, trying to reject it, trying to get rid of it, the attention moves away from it and it just becomes background noise within reason, of course.

95
00:08:10,334 --> 00:08:13,949
We get angry at people's opinions if they're not the same as ours.

96
00:08:14,550 --> 00:08:18,807
You know, this whole Brexit thing, boy, do we see some awful stuff there.

97
00:08:19,278 --> 00:08:26,247
And, of course, this is a fear that you're going to be somehow converted to their point of view.

98
00:08:26,286 --> 00:08:28,711
And that's, of course, where the pride sits.

99
00:08:29,552 --> 00:08:39,905
And so that when you hear something and you feel yourself getting irritated with the person for expressing that view, you know, we have to remind ourselves everybody has their perspective.

100
00:08:39,926 --> 00:08:46,634
And if I open up to this person's point of view, I might not agree, but at least I'll understand where they're coming from.

101
00:08:48,876 --> 00:08:53,024
Then you've got things like illness, illness that comes.

102
00:08:53,043 --> 00:09:01,258
I mean, obviously now we're suffering this COVID thing, but any illness, we don't want to be ill. That's the end of it.

103
00:09:01,337 --> 00:09:08,691
So you can be quite angry with yourself for catching a cold or angry with somebody else for giving you the flu or worse, COVID.

104
00:09:10,543 --> 00:09:11,946
And, of course, there's loss of work.

105
00:09:11,985 --> 00:09:13,288
A lot of people, loss of work.

106
00:09:13,347 --> 00:09:14,589
And that's another thing.

107
00:09:14,649 --> 00:09:22,239
That brings about a sense of depression, a sense of, you know, not wanting to bear with it.

108
00:09:24,582 --> 00:09:27,025
So patience, remember, is not resignation.

109
00:09:27,265 --> 00:09:29,067
We're not resigned to it.

110
00:09:29,830 --> 00:09:32,832
We're not rolled over by it.

111
00:09:33,293 --> 00:09:39,302
Patience is accepting things as they are and recognizing that any aversion is

112
00:09:39,485 --> 00:09:45,995
Any rejection, any trying to manipulate it for my own personal good is just causing more trouble.

113
00:09:47,157 --> 00:09:49,220
And it makes us even more angry.

114
00:09:51,182 --> 00:09:54,187
Then the Buddha talks about the four worldly conditions.

115
00:09:54,508 --> 00:09:55,769
So there's gain and loss.

116
00:09:56,350 --> 00:09:59,216
So every time we gain something, we're happy.

117
00:09:59,355 --> 00:10:01,458
When we lose it, then we're unhappy.

118
00:10:02,681 --> 00:10:03,543
And we don't like it.

119
00:10:04,023 --> 00:10:07,028
And we get angry and we get depressed and all that sort of stuff.

120
00:10:07,345 --> 00:10:30,889
and uh and it's recognizing that that's just uh not necessary it's not necessary loss comes and and that's the end of it you one one receives it one accepts it fully and if one accepts it with a good heart uh one always sees potential you know when that when that situation ends you're open and you're ready to see where the potential lies

121
00:10:33,129 --> 00:10:58,581
fame and being ignored you see you walk into a crowd and they all know you and they all greet you and all that you know and then and then you get some high idea about yourself and you walk into another crowd and they completely ignore you um or worse they think they want to ignore you and that's even worse of course so this whole idea of being uh of having lots of friends um

122
00:11:00,332 --> 00:11:08,400
In the Sangha, often you find that together because they feel comfortable in each other's company.

123
00:11:08,961 --> 00:11:16,028
But often when they mix in terms of their different nationalities, you find them, shall we say, not so open to each other.

124
00:11:16,229 --> 00:11:20,533
It's not so very nice sometimes, but it occasionally happens.

125
00:11:22,696 --> 00:11:25,077
And then, of course, there's happiness and unhappiness.

126
00:11:25,278 --> 00:11:27,780
So one minute we're happy, one minute we're unhappy.

127
00:11:28,260 --> 00:11:29,783
And you have to bear with that.

128
00:11:29,932 --> 00:11:32,174
There's no point in trying to fight it.

129
00:11:32,996 --> 00:11:46,256
And whatever is causing the unhappiness, it could be a relationship, it could be the weather, it could be the situation financially, your own personal situation.

130
00:11:47,119 --> 00:11:56,293
And again, to get angry with it, to get irritated with it, to try and get rid of it, it's all wasted energy, all wasted energy.

131
00:11:57,725 --> 00:12:01,909
And then finally he talks about praise and blame, but we all like to be praised.

132
00:12:01,929 --> 00:12:02,590
That's wonderful.

133
00:12:02,811 --> 00:12:05,793
But blame, you know, we're always trying to defend ourselves.

134
00:12:05,953 --> 00:12:09,937
Even when we've obviously done something wrong, we'll find some way of defending ourselves.

135
00:12:10,719 --> 00:12:14,202
But of course it's worse if you're blamed and you know you shouldn't be.

136
00:12:14,342 --> 00:12:17,105
I mean, that is hard to bear, hard to bear.

137
00:12:17,586 --> 00:12:20,289
But he's asking us to bear with it, you see.

138
00:12:21,691 --> 00:12:25,335
Now I just want to break off here to this delightful story of Carly.

139
00:12:25,669 --> 00:12:33,721
And this is to do with somebody who is, shall we say, pretending to be patient.

140
00:12:34,642 --> 00:12:46,317
So, formerly, in the same Sabati, so remember that's where his main monastery was, well, definitely one of his main monasteries, Anathindika, the rich merchant had bought for him.

141
00:12:47,138 --> 00:12:50,142
There was a housewife named Vedahika.

142
00:12:50,999 --> 00:12:56,745
Veda Hi Ka should be really, and a good report about Mistress Veda Hi Ka had spread thus.

143
00:12:57,386 --> 00:13:01,692
Mistress Veda Hi Ka is kind, is gentle, is peaceful.

144
00:13:02,673 --> 00:13:10,524
Now Mistress Veda Hi Ka had a maid called Kali, who was clever, nimble and neat in her work.

145
00:13:11,544 --> 00:13:15,770
The maid Kali thought a good report about my lady has spread thus.

146
00:13:16,311 --> 00:13:20,836
Mistress Veda Hi Ka is kind, is gentle, is peaceful.

147
00:13:21,424 --> 00:13:22,306
How is it now?

148
00:13:22,726 --> 00:13:28,413
While she does not show anger, is it nevertheless actually present in her, or is it?

149
00:13:29,554 --> 00:13:39,767
Or else is it just because my work is neat that my lady shows no anger, though it is actually present in her, supposing I test my lady.

150
00:13:41,009 --> 00:13:42,971
So the maid Carly got up late.

151
00:13:43,751 --> 00:13:48,217
Then Mistress Vedahika said, Hey, Carly, what is it, madam?

152
00:13:48,798 --> 00:13:50,841
What's the matter with you getting up so late?

153
00:13:51,513 --> 00:13:52,654
Nothing is the matter, madam.

154
00:13:53,255 --> 00:13:55,740
Nothing is the matter, you wicked girl.

155
00:13:56,561 --> 00:13:58,043
Yet you get up so late.

156
00:13:58,945 --> 00:14:01,950
And she was angry and displeased and she scowled.

157
00:14:03,152 --> 00:14:11,125
Then the maid thought, the fact is that while my lady does not show anger, it is actually present in her.

158
00:14:11,711 --> 00:14:12,712
It's not absent.

159
00:14:13,293 --> 00:14:20,203
And it is just because my work is neat that my lady shows no anger, though it is actually present in her, not absent.

160
00:14:20,804 --> 00:14:23,489
Supposing I test my lady a little more.

161
00:14:23,849 --> 00:14:25,091
It's a bit cheeky, really, isn't she?

162
00:14:26,273 --> 00:14:33,682
So the maid Carly got up later in the day and Mistress Vedahika said, hey, Carly, what is it, madam?

163
00:14:34,183 --> 00:14:35,245
What is the matter with you?

164
00:14:35,566 --> 00:14:37,028
You get up later today.

165
00:14:37,312 --> 00:14:39,014
Nothing is the matter, madam.

166
00:14:39,514 --> 00:14:44,282
Nothing is the matter, you wicked girl, yet you get up later in the day.

167
00:14:44,341 --> 00:14:48,628
Now she was angry and displeased, and she spoke words of displeasure.

168
00:14:49,428 --> 00:14:56,958
Then the maid Carly thought, the fact is that while my lady does not show anger, it is actually present in her, not absent.

169
00:14:57,440 --> 00:15:01,125
Suppose I test my lady a little more, wickeder.

170
00:15:01,966 --> 00:15:05,610
So the maid Carly got up still later in the day.

171
00:15:05,750 --> 00:15:09,296
Then Mistress Vedahika said, hey, Carly, what is it, madam?

172
00:15:09,917 --> 00:15:10,977
What is the matter with you?

173
00:15:10,998 --> 00:15:12,519
You got up later still today.

174
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:14,243
Nothing is the matter, madam.

175
00:15:14,663 --> 00:15:16,645
Nothing the matter, you wicked girl.

176
00:15:17,066 --> 00:15:18,969
And you get up still later in the day.

177
00:15:19,549 --> 00:15:21,471
And she was angry and displeased.

178
00:15:21,873 --> 00:15:27,179
And she took a rolling pin and gave her a blow on the head and cut her head.

179
00:15:28,392 --> 00:15:35,179
Then the maid Carly, with blood running from her cut head, denounced her mistress to her neighbours.

180
00:15:35,580 --> 00:15:38,202
See, ladies, the kind ladies work.

181
00:15:38,604 --> 00:15:41,407
See, ladies, the gentle ladies work.

182
00:15:41,807 --> 00:15:44,671
See, ladies, the peaceful ladies work.

183
00:15:44,691 --> 00:15:48,995
How can she become angry and displeased with her only maid for getting up late?

184
00:15:49,456 --> 00:15:54,062
How can she take a rolling pin, give her a blow on the head and cut her head?

185
00:15:54,682 --> 00:15:59,453
And later on, a bad report about Mistress Predajika spread about.

186
00:16:00,095 --> 00:16:01,678
Mistress Predajika is rough.

187
00:16:02,360 --> 00:16:04,885
Mistress Predajika is violent.

188
00:16:05,388 --> 00:16:09,537
Mistress Predajika is merciless.

189
00:16:10,410 --> 00:16:17,341
So often you might get somebody who doesn't show anger, but actually it's all hidden in them.

190
00:16:17,760 --> 00:16:24,750
I remember one person whom I knew who actually declared that he never felt anger.

191
00:16:25,392 --> 00:16:27,914
But of course, it was all over him.

192
00:16:28,015 --> 00:16:30,658
I mean, you could tell it a mile off that he was very angry.

193
00:16:32,662 --> 00:16:39,051
So it's a case of bearing up, bearing up what we have to suffer now.

194
00:16:40,398 --> 00:16:42,139
It's that sense of endurance.

195
00:16:42,639 --> 00:16:59,878
And of course, in our practice, there's a lot of that because when we sit, all this turbulence comes up, you know, the fears and the worries and the angers and the depressions and all the stuff that we suffer from.

196
00:17:00,298 --> 00:17:05,023
And remember that we open up to it and we open up to it with loving kindness.

197
00:17:05,064 --> 00:17:06,404
We embrace it.

198
00:17:06,875 --> 00:17:18,721
And if we can take that attitude to anything in the world that disturbs us, then obviously it just undermines this wrong relationship we have of getting angry, of not wanting to endure things.

199
00:17:20,425 --> 00:17:25,457
Of course, it gets worse because there are severe situations.

200
00:17:25,707 --> 00:17:30,010
victims of violence, and, of course, torture.

201
00:17:30,491 --> 00:17:31,392
That's the worst.

202
00:17:31,692 --> 00:17:33,595
That really is quite awful, torture.

203
00:17:33,835 --> 00:17:37,898
And we know that even our own soldiers were playing at torture.

204
00:17:38,720 --> 00:17:44,785
And that's very hard to forgive, especially when you've been really brutalised like that.

205
00:17:46,027 --> 00:17:54,734
There was a lovely book, actually, although he wasn't particularly brutalised in a way, by, I think it was Kevin Keegan, called Evil Cradling.

206
00:17:55,609 --> 00:18:25,313
and uh it goes back to the 80s i think something like that where he was hostage some of you might remember and that is definitely worth reading and his ability to forgive them this is remarkable and you'll find that you'll find people who've been terribly damaged and are able just to forgive and so forgiveness is the way out of this uh of this of this resentment of the and and and resentment towards yourself you know you have to be able to forgive yourself

207
00:18:25,866 --> 00:18:27,950
It's often a case of pride, you know.

208
00:18:27,990 --> 00:18:30,034
It's an inverted pride.

209
00:18:30,394 --> 00:18:30,934
I'm horrible.

210
00:18:30,994 --> 00:18:31,635
I'm useless.

211
00:18:31,957 --> 00:18:32,557
I'm terrible.

212
00:18:32,958 --> 00:18:34,681
I ought to live in hell.

213
00:18:37,384 --> 00:18:44,797
So, again, the Buddha gives us a wonderful simile, which many of you will know.

214
00:18:45,478 --> 00:18:47,160
It's called the simile of the saw.

215
00:18:48,823 --> 00:18:54,050
Because if bandits were to sever you savagely, limb from limb,

216
00:18:54,384 --> 00:18:56,007
with a two-handed saw.

217
00:18:56,988 --> 00:19:02,894
He who gave rise to a mind of hate towards them would not be carrying out my teaching.

218
00:19:05,877 --> 00:19:12,144
When I said this at one point, at one place, somebody said, the Buddha had a great sense of humor.

219
00:19:14,086 --> 00:19:15,628
But I think he actually means it.

220
00:19:16,569 --> 00:19:18,832
Hearing bhikkhus, you should train yourself thus.

221
00:19:19,252 --> 00:19:21,996
Our minds will remain unaffected.

222
00:19:22,364 --> 00:19:24,574
We shall utter no evil words.

223
00:19:25,036 --> 00:19:31,986
We shall abide compassionate for their welfare, with a mind of loving kindness, without inner hatred.

224
00:19:32,708 --> 00:19:56,556
we shall abide providing them with a mind imbued with loving kindness and starting with them we shall abide pervading the all-encompassing world with a mind imbued with loving kindness abundant exalted immeasurable without hostility and without ill will that is how you should train yourselves because

225
00:20:00,586 --> 00:20:11,623
If you keep this advice on the simile of the saw constantly in mind, do you see any coarse speech, trivial or gross, that you could not endure?

226
00:20:12,565 --> 00:20:13,526
No, venerable sir.

227
00:20:14,667 --> 00:20:25,023
Therefore, because you should keep this advice on the simile of the saw constantly in mind, that will lead to your welfare and happiness for a long time.

228
00:20:27,451 --> 00:20:42,220
that was what the blessed one said and the bhikkhus were satisfied and delighted in the blessed one's words so this is uh our overcoming certain um taints remember taints are

229
00:20:42,519 --> 00:20:58,119
oozings, floods, these sort of washes of negativity, of unwholesomeness that are within us, and they manifest in specific situations, specific incidences.

230
00:20:58,759 --> 00:21:10,434
Therefore, we have to have that sort of real awakenedness to catch the first movement of irritation, of anger, of rejection, of trying to change something just to make us feel more comfortable.

231
00:21:10,734 --> 00:21:24,458
uh but more that sense of opening up to the unpleasant and uh and then you see uh there's no suffering in it there's no suffering in it so i think that brings us to the end of that little particular

